
================================================================
SCOPY v1.0 - Smart Copy for CP/M 2.2
User Manual
================================================================


1. INTRODUCTION

   SCOPY is a file copy utility for CP/M 2.2 that supports
   copying files across drives and user areas. It provides
   an intuitive left-to-right command syntax, wildcard
   support, interactive mode with TAB filename completion,
   and pre-flight capacity checking.


2. COMMAND LINE USAGE

   SCOPY source destination [/options]

   Source and destination are file specifications:

     [user]drive:filename.ext

   All parts are optional:

     [user]   User area 0-15 in brackets. Defaults to
              the current user area.
     drive:   Drive letter A-P with colon. Defaults to
              the current drive.
     filename Filename, 1-8 characters. Wildcards * and ?
              are supported in the source only.
     .ext     Extension, 0-3 characters.

   The special destination "." means the current drive and
   current user area.


3. EXAMPLES

   SCOPY FILE.COM B:
     Copy FILE.COM from the current drive/user to B:.

   SCOPY B:FILE.COM .
     Copy FILE.COM from B: to the current drive/user.

   SCOPY *.MAC B:
     Copy all .MAC files to B:.

   SCOPY [3]FILE.COM [5]B:
     Copy FILE.COM from user 3 on the current drive
     to user 5 on B:.

   SCOPY [0]A:*.COM [3]B:
     Copy all .COM files from user 0 on A: to user 3
     on B:.

   SCOPY *.ASM [2]
     Copy all .ASM files to user 2 on the current drive.

   SCOPY FOO.COM B:BAR.COM
     Copy FOO.COM to B: and rename it to BAR.COM.
     Rename is only allowed for single file copies,
     not with wildcards.


4. OPTIONS

   Options are specified after the destination, preceded
   by a forward slash. Multiple flags can be combined.

   /V   Verify each file after copying by reading back
        the destination and comparing it byte-for-byte
        with the source. Displays "OK, Verified" on
        success or "Verify FAILED" on mismatch.

   /C   Confirm each file before copying. SCOPY prompts
        "Copy FILENAME.EXT? (Y/N)" for each file. Press
        Y to copy or any other key to skip.

   /R   Replace existing files without prompting. By
        default, SCOPY asks before overwriting. This
        flag suppresses the overwrite prompt.

   /Q   Quiet mode. Suppresses per-file output. Only
        the summary and any errors are displayed.

   Flags may be combined: /VC or specified separately:
   /V /C

   Examples:
     SCOPY *.COM B: /V
     SCOPY *.* [3]B: /RC
     SCOPY *.MAC B: /V /Q


5. INTERACTIVE MODE

   Running SCOPY with no arguments (or with only flags)
   enters interactive mode:

     I>SCOPY
     SCOPY v1.0 - Smart Copy for CP/M 2.2
     Source: _
     Dest:   _

   If only the source is given on the command line, SCOPY
   prompts for the destination:

     I>SCOPY *.COM
     Dest:   _

   Flags can be specified on the command line before
   entering interactive mode:

     I>SCOPY /V
     Source: _

5.1. TAB Filename Completion

   In interactive mode, pressing TAB completes the
   filename you are typing:

     Source: SC         <press TAB>
     Source: SCOPY.MAC  <completed>

   Each subsequent TAB press cycles to the next matching
   filename. After the last match, it wraps to the first.
   If no files match the partial name, the terminal bell
   sounds.

   TAB completion works with user area and drive prefixes:

     Source: [2]B:AS    <press TAB>
     Source: [2]B:ASM.COM

   The user/drive prefix stays on screen; only the
   filename portion cycles.

   TAB is ignored if the partial input contains wildcard
   characters (* or ?).

5.2. Line Editing

   The following keys are available in interactive mode:

     Backspace   Delete the last character
     DELETE      Same as Backspace
     RETURN      Accept the current input
     CTRL-C      Abort and exit SCOPY
     TAB         Filename completion (see above)


6. PRE-FLIGHT CHECKS

   Before copying, SCOPY validates:

   - The source file(s) exist
   - The destination has enough free disk space
   - The destination has enough free directory entries
   - You are not copying a file onto itself

   If any check fails, SCOPY displays an error with
   details and exits without copying.

   If all checks pass, a summary is displayed:

     Source: [0]A:*.COM (5 files, 48K)
     Dest:   [3]B:      (112K free, 38 dir entries free)


7. COPY OPERATION

   Files are copied using all available memory as a
   buffer. Large files are handled automatically with
   multiple read/write passes.

   Files are copied by record count, not by scanning
   for end-of-file markers. This ensures binary files
   (such as .COM programs) are copied correctly even
   if they contain embedded CTRL-Z bytes.

   During the copy, each file's progress is shown:

     Copying STAT.COM ...OK
     Copying PIP.COM ...OK
     Copying ASM.COM ...OK, Verified

   After all files are copied, a summary is displayed:

     3 file(s) copied, 48K transferred


8. OVERWRITE BEHAVIOR

   If a destination file already exists:

   - By default, SCOPY prompts:
     "Overwrite FILENAME.EXT? (Y/N)"
     Press Y to overwrite, or any other key to skip.

   - With /R, existing files are replaced without
     prompting.

   - If the existing file is marked Read-Only, SCOPY
     clears the R/O attribute before overwriting.

   File attributes (Read-Only, System, Archive) are
   preserved from the source file after copying.


9. ERROR MESSAGES

   No matching files
     The source file specification did not match any
     files on the source drive/user.

   Cannot copy file to itself
     The source and destination resolve to the same
     drive, user area, and filename.

   Insufficient disk space (need XXK, have XXK)
     The destination drive does not have enough free
     space for the files to be copied.

   Insufficient directory space (need XX, have XX free)
     The destination drive does not have enough free
     directory entries for the file extents.

   Rename not allowed with wildcards
     A destination filename was specified together with
     wildcards in the source. Rename only works for
     single file copies.

   Read error / Write error
     A disk I/O error occurred during the copy.

   Cannot create file / Cannot open file
     The file could not be created or opened. The
     directory may be full or the disk may have errors.

   Cannot delete file
     An existing destination file could not be deleted,
     even after clearing the Read-Only attribute.

   Verify FAILED
     The read-back comparison did not match. The copied
     file may be corrupt. Check the destination disk.


10. LIMITATIONS

   - Requires CP/M 2.2 or compatible
   - Maximum user area: 15
   - Maximum files per wildcard: 128
   - Wildcard rename is not supported
   - TAB completion shows up to 64 matches


11. HELP

   Type SCOPY /? at the command prompt for a quick
   usage summary.


